            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            <p>This is a postcard sent by Thomas Dolan (d.1917) to his sister. The postcard was written on 11 May, the day before the final executions of the leaders of the Rising. Tom writes to ensure his sister that he is safe and to show her the damage done in Dublin. The postcard is an image of the badly damage Liberty Hall, headquarters of the Irish Transport and General Workers Union. Many of those who took part in the Rising set out from Liberty Hall on its opening day. It was shelled by a British gunboat during the fighting but was empty at the time.</p>
                        
                            <p>Tom Dolan served with the British Army at the time of the 1916 Rising. Having taken part in the suppression, he would go on to serve in Belgium, where he was killed in action on the opening day of the second battle of Passchendaele, 26 October 1917.</p>
                        
                    
                </note>
            </notesStmt>
